## Content
````
The file `dotnet\tests\microsoft.agents.ai.hosting.openai.unittests\testhelpers.cs`, designated by the namespace `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests`, contains the class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers`. This class is an integral component within a series of unit testing utilities primarily focused on AI hosting services provided by OpenAI. The class operates as a structured collection of mock implementations, accommodating various types of content interactions such as text, image, audio, and mixed format to ensure comprehensive testing capacity.

Although the class itself lacks explicit implementation in the provided code snippet, it serves as a namespace housing multiple internal sealed mock classes conforming to the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.IChatClient` interface. Each mock class within this namespace is designed to simulate distinct types of chat client activities, such as `SimpleMockChatClient` for basic text responses, `ImageContentMockChatClient` for handling image data, and `AudioContentMockChatClient` for audio interactions. These mock implementations provide developers the ability to test chat systems without requiring real-time interaction with AI models or genuine data processing.

The operational scope of these mock classes includes methods like `GetResponseAsync` and `GetStreamingResponseAsync`, which are responsible for synchronous and asynchronous response generation utilizing constructs such as `Task` and `IAsyncEnumerable`. These facilitate real-time simulation and incremental data delivery analogous to actual AI-driven chat systems. Moreover, each class boasts a `GetService` method, which emulates dependency injection patterns to fetch instances for specific service types. This intern architectural choice allows for improved reusability and extensibility across various testing scenarios.

In terms of interactions and dependencies, these mock classes are encapsulated with internal configurations, operating independent of external libraries to mitigate instability risks. The lack of direct AI model integration streamlines the testing process, allowing for rapid iterations and consistent output. The constructor parameterization, notably in `CustomContentMockChatClient`, provides flexibility, enabling testers to define custom logic as per evolving test requirements, illustrating the adaptability of the framework to align with shifting functional specifications.

By organizing these mock implementations under a unified namespace, the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers` class effectively equips developers with the necessary tools to rigorously assess AI chat interactions, validate response handling, and predictably ensure performance consistency in client applications dependent on OpenAI solutions.

## Content
````
The `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers` class is a pivotal component within Microsoft’s unit testing framework for their AI hosting services, specifically integrating mock implementations for OpenAI-related functionalities. Although devoid of its distinct body and methods, this class encapsulates several internal sealed mock classes that implement the `IChatClient` interface to adequately test various aspects of AI-driven chat systems. The primary objective of this class is to provide a structured namespace wherein multiple mock chat clients can be developed and utilized, offering a unified interface for developers to conduct comprehensive unit testing without requiring interaction with actual AI models or processing live inputs.

The class comprises several designated sub-modules: `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient`, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient`, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient`, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient`, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient`, and `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient`. Each module serves a distinct purpose by generating controlled responses based on input scenarios. For example, `SimpleMockChatClient` offers basic text responses, whereas `ImageContentMockChatClient` and `AudioContentMockChatClient` simulate interactions with image and audio content respectively. This versatility allows developers to tailor their test cases specifically to verify chat client behaviors, resource usage, and service retrieval operations in varied contexts.

Each mock class typically includes methods such as `GetResponseAsync` and `GetStreamingResponseAsync` to handle synchronous and asynchronous response generation. These methods often utilize C# constructs like `Task` and `IAsyncEnumerable`, simulating real-time processing and incremental data delivery pertinent in AI-driven chat applications. The `GetService` method in each class establishes service resolution, emulating dependency injection patterns by ensuring that appropriate instances are returned when queried for particular service types. This adherence to a service-oriented architecture promotes reuse and extensibility across diverse testing scenarios, aiding in consistent code quality assurance.

Interactions within these mock classes are contained, relying predominantly on internal configurations and predefined responses. Consequently, dependencies on external libraries or systems are minimized, enhancing stability and scalability within the testing environment. The absence of actual AI model interactions ensures that these tests remain lightweight, facilitating rapid iterations and consistency in output across subsequent testing cycles. Parameterization within constructors — particularly evident in classes like `CustomContentMockChatClient` — offers flexibility, allowing testers to specify custom logic that aligns with evolving testing requirements.

Overall, the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers` class and its associated mock implementations play an essential role in fostering robust unit testing frameworks. By organizing these various mock clients under a common namespace, developers are equipped with a toolkit to rigorously examine AI chat interactions, validate response handling mechanisms, and ensure predictable performance in client applications reliant on OpenAI technologies.

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient` is a mock implementation of the `IChatClient` interface, designed to facilitate unit testing within Microsoft's AI hosting framework involving OpenAI. Its primary purpose is to simulate the behavior of a chat client that processes audio content, by providing predefined responses without needing actual audio processing. This class is part of a testing infrastructure, allowing developers to test audio content handling consistently and predictably.

Key components of the `AudioContentMockChatClient` include its constructor and several methods. The constructor initializes instances with predefined audio data and a transcript, converting a given string representing audio data into a byte array using UTF8 encoding, and storing both the audio data and transcript for later use. The `GetResponseAsync` method provides mocked synchronous chat responses by generating a `ChatResponse` object. This object includes an embedded audio message and relevant metadata like a `ModelId`, finish reason, and token usage statistics. The method mimics the expected behavior by leveraging predefined responses, ensuring repeatable test outcomes.

Another vital method, `GetStreamingResponseAsync`, implements asynchronous streaming of chat responses using C#'s `IAsyncEnumerable`. This method simulates streaming by yielding `ChatResponseUpdate` objects with embedded audio content and associated properties such as a transcript and token usage metrics. The method performs an initial non-blocking delay to ensure it aligns with asynchronous execution models, then continuously provides updates until a logical conclusion. This allows for testing interactions that depend on sequential processing of streamed audio data.

Moreover, the `GetService` method provides dependency resolution by checking if the current instance can satisfy a requested service type. If suitable, it returns the instance itself, supporting service-oriented architectures commonly used in dependency injection. The class implements the `IDisposable` interface through an empty `Dispose` method. This method does not perform any actual resource disposal but ensures the class can be integrated seamlessly with patterns that expect disposable resources, such as the `using` statement in C#.

Overall, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient` utilizes predefined data to mimic a chat client that handles audio inputs, serving as a robust tool for testing interactions with audio content within the Microsoft AI framework environment. This setup ensures that developers can confidently test parts of their application logic concerning audio content without engaging with real audio data processing, providing reliability and efficiency in the unit testing process.

The constructor `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient.AudioContentMockChatClient` is designed to initialize instances of the `AudioContentMockChatClient` class with specific audio data and transcript information for unit testing purposes. It transforms a string representing audio data into a byte array using UTF8 encoding, which is stored in the private field `_audioData`. Additionally, it assigns a string transcript to the private field `_transcript`. This constructor enables the instantiation of test client objects with predefined audio and transcript values, aiding in the simulation of audio content processing without actual audio files. No conditional logic or iterative processes are present in this constructor, as its function is straightforward: converting a base64 string to a byte array and storing a transcript string. Dependencies involve the `System.Text.Encoding.UTF8` class from the .NET framework for encoding operations. This setup is essential for unit tests, ensuring that developers can consistently replicate test scenarios involving audio data handling.
````

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is an asynchronous method designed to simulate a chat response within a testing context. Its primary purpose is to provide a mock implementation of generating a `ChatResponse` based on input `ChatMessage` objects, alongside optional `ChatOptions` and a `CancellationToken`. The function constructs a single `ChatMessage` with the role of `ChatRole.Assistant`. It contains embedded audio data represented by `DataContent` with the MIME type "audio/wav". An additional dictionary stores a "transcript" property linking to a private field `_transcript`.

The response is wrapped in a `ChatResponse` object initialized with the constructed message (using `new ChatResponse([message])`). It incorporates properties such as `ModelId` set to "test-model", `FinishReason` set to `ChatFinishReason.Stop`, and `Usage` details specifying token counts: `InputTokenCount` of 10, `OutputTokenCount` of 5, and a `TotalTokenCount` of 15. The function concludes by returning this response immediately using `Task.FromResult(response)`, facilitating seamless function execution without actual processing or network interactions. This setup allows engineers to consistently simulate the expected behavior of chat interactions in controlled test scenarios.
````

## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient.GetService` is designed to retrieve a service implementation for a given type, `Type serviceType`, optionally using a `serviceKey`. It performs a simple check to determine if the current instance (`this`) is compatible with the requested service type using the `IsInstanceOfType` method. Specifically, it checks if the service type is assignable from the instance type of the object in which the method is being invoked. If the instance is of the requested type, the method returns the current instance; otherwise, it returns `null`. 

This method plays a role in dependency resolution and injection typically seen in service container scenarios or mocking frameworks for unit tests. It does not rely on external systems or libraries beyond inheriting functionality from the base `object` class. The optional parameter `serviceKey` is accepted, but it is not utilized within the method's logic, suggesting that its implementation may be extended in the future or it remains as a placeholder. Differences in parameter calling, particularly with the `serviceType`, will determine if the method returns the current instance or `null`, making type compatibility a crucial factor in its operations. A sample invocation in a test might look like `var service = chatClient.GetService(typeof(MyService));`, where `chatClient` is an instance of `AudioContentMockChatClient` and `MyService` is expected to match the client's type.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.AudioContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` aims to provide an asynchronous streaming chat response by implementing `IAsyncEnumerable`. It takes a collection of `ChatMessage` objects, `ChatOptions`, and an optional cancellation token to manage asynchronous operations. Upon being invoked, the function performs an initial non-blocking delay using `await Task.Delay(1, cancellationToken)` to ensure readiness for asynchronous execution. Then, it immediately yields a `ChatResponseUpdate` object containing transformed audio data. Specifically, the `ChatResponseUpdate` consists of `Contents` that include a `DataContent` initialized with audio data in the format "audio/wav." This is enriched with additional properties like a transcript, stored in an `AdditionalPropertiesDictionary`. Furthermore, the `ChatResponseUpdate` contains `UsageContent`, detailing token count statistics that track input, output, and total tokens utilized: `InputTokenCount`, `OutputTokenCount`, and `TotalTokenCount`. The function concludes by designating the role as `ChatRole.Assistant`, emulating a chat interaction scenario typical for conversational agent architectures. The function embraces asynchronous programming, contributing to scalable and responsive design, and uses a cancellation token to handle potential interruptions, ensuring robust operation under varying execution states and system loads.

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient` is designed as a mock implementation of the `IChatClient` interface to facilitate unit testing scenarios without relying on actual AI communication systems. Its main purpose is to simulate chat client behavior by outputting predetermined responses via a custom content provider function. This setup allows testers to verify how chat systems handle and render content without incurring the overhead of real-time interactions with AI models.

The class is structured around several key methods: the constructor `CustomContentMockChatClient`, `GetResponseAsync`, `GetStreamingResponseAsync`, `GetService`, and `Dispose`. The constructor accepts a delegate, `Func<ChatMessage, IEnumerable<AIContent>>`, that takes a `ChatMessage` and produces an enumerable of `AIContent`. This delegate is integral to the class's ability to generate and supply custom content based on incoming chat messages. The `GetResponseAsync` method synchronously returns a `ChatResponse` object formulated with content produced by the delegate, simulating a typical chat response from an AI assistant role. It encapsulates model metadata and resource usage statistics for accurately representing AI-generated responses.

In contrast, `GetStreamingResponseAsync` acts as an asynchronous generator that provides streams of `ChatResponseUpdate` objects, each derived from individual entries of `AIContent` sourced from the latest `ChatMessage`. This method introduces minimal artificial delay to emulate asynchronous streaming, with the option to cancel the operation using a `CancellationToken`. Usage statistics are appended in the final streamed response to give comprehensive details about token consumption, thus mimicking dynamic chat contexts where feedback is progressively built.

The method `GetService` delivers runtime type-checking, ensuring the instance can potentially satisfy service requests based on type compatibility, whereas `Dispose` serves as an empty placeholder aligning with the `IDisposable` interface, suggesting readiness for resource management enhancements when necessary. The class, being internally sealed, focuses exclusively on unit testing by generating deterministic responses and thus lacks complex conditional branching. This simplicity considerably enhances its utility for validating chat-related functionalities.

The `CustomContentMockChatClient` leverages no external libraries apart from standard .NET constructs, thereby ensuring straightforward integration into testing frameworks. Its parameter design enhances flexibility, as varied content generation strategies can be invoked by altering the delegate function signature. The modular nature of the class ensures that it can easily adapt to different testing scenarios by substituting the custom logic encapsulated within the content provider delegate.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient.CustomContentMockChatClient` is a constructor for the `CustomContentMockChatClient` class, designed to initialize an instance of this class. Its primary purpose is to set up the class by assigning a delegate function to a private field named `_contentProvider`. The constructor takes one parameter, `contentProvider`, which is of type `Func<ChatMessage, IEnumerable<AIContent>>`. This parameter represents a function that, when invoked, accepts a `ChatMessage` object and returns an `IEnumerable` of `AIContent` objects, effectively serving as a content generation mechanism. The constructor binds this function to the class member `_contentProvider`, enabling other methods in the class to utilize this function for generating or mocking chat content when needed. This setup does not involve any complex control structures such as loops or conditionals, as its sole responsibility is the initialization of the field with the provided delegate. There are no external interactions or dependencies introduced within this constructor apart from the reliance on the `Func<ChatMessage, IEnumerable<AIContent>>` delegate, which implies that the class is extendable to accommodate different content generation strategies by altering the provided function signature.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is designed to asynchronously generate a mocked response for a chat application using a custom content provider. The function first retrieves the latest `ChatMessage` from the provided `messages` collection using the `Last()` method. It processes this message to produce AI-generated content using a private method `_contentProvider`, transforming it into a list of `AIContent` objects. Subsequently, a new `ChatMessage` initialized with a role of `ChatRole.Assistant` and the generated contents is wrapped into a `ChatResponse` object. This object is configured with hard-coded properties: the model ID as "test-model", the finish reason as `ChatFinishReason.Stop`, and usage metrics set with predetermined token counts. The function ultimately returns a completed task encapsulating this response using `Task.FromResult()`, effectively simulating the completion of an asynchronous operation without actual delay. The function's simplicity ensures immediate execution, primarily serving as a test utility for unit tests where dependencies and side effects (e.g., actual communications with external AI systems) are minimized, hence allowing predictable control over response data.
````

## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient.GetService` is implemented to provide a mechanism for fetching a service based on its type, optionally using a service key. The function signature specifies that it returns an object, potentially null, and accepts two parameters: `serviceType` of type `System.Type` and an optional `serviceKey` of type object. The logic within the function employs a conditional expression that checks if the `serviceType` matches the type of the instance from which the method is invoked (`this`). This is executed using the `IsInstanceOfType` method, which determines if a specified instance is of the type represented by the `serviceType` parameter. If the check passes, the function returns the current instance (`this`); otherwise, it returns `null`, signifying that the requested service is not provided by the current object.

This function is structured simply, performing a direct comparison without complex branching or loops, indicating a singular check against the type of the executing context. A key aspect of this design is its reliance on type checking at runtime, which ensures compatibility of the requested service with the executing object, thereby providing a safeguard against type errors. The optional `serviceKey` parameter, despite being present, is not utilized within the function, highlighting a potential for future extensions where service differentiation might be required based on keys. This function acts as part of the test helpers in unit tests for mock client interactions, specifically designed to simulate behaviors expected from service providers.

- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.CustomContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` method is an asynchronous generator (`IAsyncEnumerable`) designed to produce a sequence of `ChatResponseUpdate` objects. This method operates within the context of a mock chat client intended for unit testing purposes. It accepts an enumerable of `ChatMessage` objects and optionally a `ChatOptions` parameter, along with a `CancellationToken`. Initially, it introduces a minuscule delay using `Task.Delay`, allowing for potential cancellation. It determines the last chat message from the `messages` collection, uses an internal content provider method (`_contentProvider`) to retrieve AI-generated content associated with that message into a list (`contentList`), and then iterates over each content item. During the iteration, it wraps individual content items into a list (`updateContents`). Specifically, for the last item in the iteration, `UsageContent` data containing `UsageDetails` is appended to provide token usage statistics. This facilitates streaming of structured chat responses, which are yielded back to the caller as `ChatResponseUpdate` objects containing the prepared content and designating the response role as `ChatRole.Assistant`. This method effectively enables integration with asynchronous data flow systems and can be utilized for streaming chat-like data during unit tests.
````

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient` serves as a mock implementation of the `IChatClient` interface within its namespace, providing simulated responses representative of function calls. It is structured as a sealed class to prevent further subclassing, and all elements defined within it focus specifically on unit testing scenarios. The class encapsulates private instance variables such as `_functionName` and `_arguments`, which are initialized via its constructor. These variables hold the function name and a dictionary parsed from a JSON string of arguments, enabling the simulation of dynamic function-call behaviors during the testing process.

Central to its implementation is the asynchronous method `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`, which takes a collection of `ChatMessage` objects alongside optional `ChatOptions` and a `CancellationToken`. The function constructs a static `ChatResponse`, comprising predefined model and usage details, designed to mimic interaction with a chat service, focusing solely on returning consistent data for validation purposes. This asynchronous method ensures that any external dependencies or latency variances don't interfere with mock data generation, streamlining unit test stability.

Moreover, the class supports asynchronous streaming through the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` method. This method yields a single `ChatResponseUpdate` after a simulated delay of one millisecond, integrating mock components such as `FunctionCallContent` and `UsageContent` into the response. Structured as an `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>`, it offers real-time data emission suitable for testing systems that require adaptive responses and can handle streamed data efficiently.

Dependency management is addressed with the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetService` method, which verifies type compatibility between service requests and the current instance. This functionality aligns with the principles of service-oriented architecture, providing robust type verification to avoid unintended access to resources. Additionally, resource lifecycle management is established through the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.Dispose` method, although presently without concrete disposal operations, it sets a standardized entry point for future resource cleanup necessities as dictated by the `IDisposable` interface.

Overall, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient` is intricately tailored for testing environments, ensuring uniform and predictable chat response simulation without interacting with actual external systems. This consistency aids in evaluating the handling of responses and assessing the logic encapsulated within potential consumer implementations by maintaining isolation and simplifying setup for test environments.

## Content
````
The constructor `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.FunctionCallMockChatClient` is designed to initialize instances of the `FunctionCallMockChatClient` class with specified parameters for the simulated function call. It accepts two optional parameters: `functionName` and `arguments`. The default value for `functionName` is "test_function", and the default for `arguments` is the JSON string `{"param":"value"}`. Upon invocation, it assigns the provided `functionName` to the instance variable `_functionName`. It then parses the `arguments` JSON string into a `Dictionary<string, object?>` using the `System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Deserialize` method. If the deserialization results in a null value, it defaults to an empty dictionary. This configuration enables mock interactions that simulate function calls by dynamically assigning arguments and parsing them into structured key-value pairs. This mechanism can be utilized in unit tests to validate input handling and function invocation logic, ensuring proper simulation and assessment of functionality within the broader software ecosystem. The simplicity of parameter handling ensures scalability when accommodating diverse input scenarios, although the constructor does not currently incorporate conditionals or loops.

The method `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is designed to simulate an asynchronous operation that returns a static `ChatResponse`. It accepts a collection of `ChatMessage` objects and an optional `ChatOptions` parameter, along with a `CancellationToken` with a default value. Internally, the method constructs a `ChatMessage` representing an assistant role, encoding a mock function call with a name and arguments stored in the `FunctionCallContent`. This `ChatMessage` is encapsulated within a `ChatResponse` object initialized with several static properties: `ModelId` set to "test-model", a completion reason of `ChatFinishReason.ToolCalls`, and predefined usage statistics indicating token counts. The function bypasses any complex logic, conditional branching, or loops, consistently returning a `Task` containing this pre-fabricated `ChatResponse`. 

No external systems are invoked, and no dynamic computation or state handling occurs; this isolation renders the function a suitable test mock to check interactions without side effects. Key dependencies such as `ChatMessage`, `ChatRole`, `FunctionCallContent`, `ChatResponse`, and `UsageDetails` classes or structures suggest a framework setup tailored to emulate API-generated chat responses. The consistent, synchronous task return pattern and absence of dynamic input processing underline the mock nature, focusing on testing the consumer's ability to handle returned data structures rather than response generation. This simplicity ensures stable unit testing without variable external factors impacting results.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetService` is designed to retrieve a service instance based on the specified `Type`. It is a method that determines whether the current instance (`this`) is an assignable type of the requested service type. This is achieved through the use of the `IsInstanceOfType` method, which checks if the instance can be treated as the desired service type. If the type check passes, the function returns the current instance; otherwise, it returns `null`. The method signature includes an optional parameter `serviceKey`, but the implementation does not utilize it, suggesting its presence for interface compliance or future extensibility purposes. The function operates without any external dependencies, logical branches, or loops, presenting a straightforward mechanism of type verification and conditional return. The design ensures type safety by only allowing service retrieval when type compatibility is assured. Consequently, differing parameter calling with incorrect or unrelated types would result in the method returning `null`, thereby preventing unintended service access or interaction.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.FunctionCallMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` is designed to stream chat responses asynchronously as instances of `ChatResponseUpdate`. It processes a collection of `ChatMessage` objects along with optional `ChatOptions` while considering a `CancellationToken` for operation cancellation. Upon invocation, it initiates a minimal `Task.Delay` for 1 millisecond using the specified cancellation token to simulate an asynchronous operation. Then, it yields a single `ChatResponseUpdate` containing predefined content structured as a list. This list includes a `FunctionCallContent` object, initialized with a hardcoded function call identifier `call_123` and a function name (`this._functionName`), alongside dynamically set arguments (`this._arguments`). Additionally, it encapsulates a `UsageContent` object initialized with fixed token counts detailing input (`80`), output (`25`), and total count (`105`). The response object is further characterized by an `Assistant` role, as defined in the `ChatRole` enumeration.

The function leverages asynchronous streaming through the `IAsyncEnumerable<T>` return type, allowing for gradually yielded results, potentially useful in constructing real-time, responsive systems. While no conditional logic or iterations are evident beyond the single yield statement, the main functionality focuses on providing a structured mock chat response for testing purposes, assuming collaboration with external dependencies to emphasize internal implementation over scalability considerations. This setup indicates that modifications to parameters like continuation tokens or dynamic token counts might affect how the streaming response adjusts to interaction demands. Overall, it simulates the behavior of a chat client responding to input messages while handling asynchronous data flow through mocked components suitable for unit testing scenarios.

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient` is a mocked implementation designed for unit testing scenarios where developers simulate AI-driven chat client interactions, particularly with image content responses. It implements the `IChatClient` interface to ensure compatibility with expected client functionalities and behaviors, including asynchronous message handling and service retrieval. The primary purpose of this class is to facilitate controlled testing environments by providing predefined responses, reducing the complexity of integrating actual AI models or external services during development and testing phases.

The class structure is organized around a set of functions that simulate chat interactions. The constructor, `ImageContentMockChatClient.ImageContentMockChatClient`, initializes instances with a default image URL, allowing this URL to be overridden by a caller-provided parameter. This supports versatility in testing scenarios by enabling image URL variation across different tests. The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` constructs mock `ChatResponse` objects, embedding both text and URI contents to mimic real-world responses from AI chat models. This enables validation of image-text integration logic within an application's response handling capabilities.

Another key function, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`, leverages asynchronous programming capabilities in C# to yield streaming `ChatResponseUpdate` objects. This function uses an `IAsyncEnumerable` to simulate partial and iterative response delivery, mimicking scenarios where chat responses arrive incrementally. By incorporating delay and yielding control to other tasks, the class reflects realistic asynchronous operation that could occur in a live chat environment, aiding in testing robustness under varied operational conditions.

The method `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetService` exemplifies dynamic service retrieval using type checks, allowing the class to support flexible dependency injection patterns. This aligns with architectural best practices whereby services can be resolved dynamically based on their type rather than concrete implementations. Meanwhile, the `Dispose` method remains intentionally empty, adhering to proper interface structure but indicating no immediate unmanaged resource management within the class.

Overall, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient` serves as a foundational test helper module, illustrating techniques for testing image content interactions in chat applications. Its design supports extensibility and scalable testing, ensuring developers can accurately simulate, observe, and validate chat client behaviors and environmental dynamics without engaging actual AI systems or external dependencies.

# Summary of `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
- Id: `LohBj4xS1re72uHpnas/GrOVNahhfSFxeCpF3sfUezg=`
- Kind: `Symbol`
- Symbol: `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
- SymbolType: `Function`
- Path: `c:\src\alliscode-agent-framework\dotnet\tests\microsoft.agents.ai.hosting.openai.unittests\testhelpers.cs`
## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is designed to create and asynchronously return a mock `ChatResponse` object, simulating a response from an AI model with image data integration. It constructs a `ChatMessage` object, with the role of `ChatRole.Assistant`, containing two types of content: a `TextContent` displaying the message "Here is an image:" and a `UriContent` representing an image located at the URL stored in the private field `this._imageUrl`, with an "image/png" MIME type. This message is encapsulated within the `ChatResponse` object, which includes metadata such as `ModelId` set to "test-model", a `FinishReason` indicating the response has reached a stopping point (`ChatFinishReason.Stop`), and token usage details (`UsageDetails`) indicating input, output, and total tokens processed during this mock session. The function returns this response wrapped as a `Task<ChatResponse>`, utilizing `Task.FromResult(response)` for a synchronous completion. Interactions involve predefined mock objects and types, requiring an understanding of underlying data structures such as `TextContent`, `UriContent`, and role/state identifiers like `ChatRole` and `ChatFinishReason`. This function enables developers to test and validate interaction logic involving image content, ensuring that the application can accurately form and process structured chat responses even in a test environment.

The function uses a simple, efficient mechanism to determine if the current instance (`this`) is of the specified `serviceType`. It achieves this through the method `serviceType.IsInstanceOfType(this)`, which checks if the type of `this` is compatible with `serviceType`. If the instance matches the expected service type, it returns `this`; otherwise, it returns `null`, indicating that the service type is not available in the current instance. This mechanism allows for dynamic retrieval of services where the consumer of the function can decide what type of instance to consider as a service.

The structure of the function highlights a straightforward conditional check without additional conditional branches or complex control flows. Despite the optional parameter `serviceKey`, the function design does not incorporate its logic, suggesting that key-based service retrieval is unsupported or unused in this implementation. This function is critical for dependency injection or service management patterns, where a client may seek to obtain services dynamically based on type rather than a concrete implementation. Thus, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetService` facilitates flexible architecture patterns by allowing objects to decide at runtime if they fulfill a particular service contract, supporting extension and simplification of integration across different components within the application ecosystem.

## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` is an asynchronous method that returns an `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>` stream. It takes a collection of `ChatMessage` objects and an optional `ChatOptions` parameter, along with a `CancellationToken` marked for enumeration cancellation. The function first introduces a negligible delay via `await Task.Delay(1, cancellationToken)`, though this delay serves no functional purpose beyond potentially yielding control to other tasks. The method then uses yield statements to provide two `ChatResponseUpdate` objects sequentially. The first update contains a `TextContent` object with a simple message "Here is an image:", and designates the role as `ChatRole.Assistant`. The second update includes both a `UriContent` with an image URL (`this._imageUrl`) specifying "image/png" as the media type and a `UsageContent` object encapsulating a `UsageDetails` instance. The usage details include `InputTokenCount`, `OutputTokenCount`, and `TotalTokenCount`, set to 10, 5, and 15 respectively, indicating token usage metrics. The structure of this function indicates it could be used to simulate streaming chat responses with varying content, representing both text and media elements, within a mock unit testing environment. This function specifically highlights the simulated interaction of sending response updates as part of a broader chat client framework, with implications for testing scenarios where asynchronous and partial message responses are key components.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.ImageContentMockChatClient.ImageContentMockChatClient` is a constructor designed to initialize instances of the `ImageContentMockChatClient` class with an image URL. It assigns a default URL, "https://example.com/image.png", to the `_imageUrl` private field, although the caller can override this default by providing their own URL value as a parameter. Structurally, the constructor consists of parameters defaulted to a specific image URL for versatility, allowing flexibility in the instantiation process by accepting alternative URLs. By setting the default parameter in the constructor, it ensures that the class can be used without requiring explicit URL input, which aids in simplifying unit tests or mock implementations. The constructor does not interact with external systems or libraries beyond assigning a string value, positioning its role as a foundational component for simulating chat client behavior within unit testing contexts.

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient` serves as a mock implementation of the `IChatClient` interface, specifically designed for use in unit testing within the Microsoft Agents AI Hosting framework. The primary purpose of this class is to simulate various functionalities of a real chat client, such as generating chat responses and handling mixed content types without actual integration into an OpenAI service. This is achieved by implementing several methods that adhere to typical chat client behaviors but within a controlled, predictable test environment.

Key components of the class include four methods: `GetResponseAsync`, `GetStreamingResponseAsync`, `GetService`, and `Dispose`. The `GetResponseAsync` method is asynchronous and returns a static `ChatResponse` object representing predefined mixed content, which includes multiple `TextContent` and `UriContent` elements. It neatly encapsulates usage metrics such as token counts and adheres to patterns observed in real OpenAI chat responses. The method operates asynchronously using `Task.CompletedTask`, advancing unit test scenarios by offering predictable outputs based on static inputs.

The `GetStreamingResponseAsync` method, also asynchronous, differs by employing `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>`, simulating streaming responses. It utilizes `yield return` to sequentially output multiple `ChatResponseUpdate` instances containing mixed chat content. Each update showcases differing types of content such as text, images via URIs, and usage details. This method is particularly useful in tests that require verifying incremental receipt and processing of chat data over time.

The `GetService` method facilitates service retrieval based on type checking, using the `Type.IsInstanceOfType` mechanism. This function checks if the current instance matches a specified service type, either returning the instance or `null`. Such functionality is integrable into frameworks lacking built-in dependency injection capabilities, ensuring adherence to service-oriented architecture principles. The `Dispose` method, though currently devoid of logic, ensures compliance with the `IDisposable` interface, allowing consistent cleanup patterns even when explicit resource management is unnecessary.

The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient` does not engage external systems directly but rather uses dependencies like `IEnumerable<ChatMessage>`, `ChatOptions`, and various content-related constructs to simulate the real-world chat interactions and the complexity associated with mixed content types. This approach grants developers the ability to test their integration with AI chat clients effectively, ensuring their application's handling of potential real-world scenarios while maintaining protocol adherence and avoiding resource leaks.

## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
## Content
````
`Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is an asynchronous method designed to simulate generating a chat response. The method accepts `IEnumerable<ChatMessage>` as input messages, an optional `ChatOptions`, and a `CancellationToken`, with default values. It constructs a mock `ChatMessage` representing the assistant's role, encapsulating mixed content: multiple `TextContent` and a `UriContent` with a specified URI and MIME type. The `ChatResponse`, built from this mock message, is configured with static attributes. This includes a model identifier "test-model", a completion reason using `ChatFinishReason.Stop`, and detailed token usage in a `UsageDetails` object reflecting input, output, and total token counts. The method concludes by returning this `ChatResponse` wrapped within a completed `Task`, effectively simulating a predictable completion scenario without any conditional branches or iteration constructs, asserting its function predominantly as a mock utility in unit tests for handling composite chat content scenarios.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient.GetService` is designed to retrieve an instance of a service object based on its type, optionally factoring in a service key. This method accepts two parameters: `serviceType` of the `Type` class, which indicates the desired service's type, and an optional `serviceKey` of type `object?`. The method employs a conditional check using `Type.IsInstanceOfType`, which determines if the current instance (`this`) matches the `serviceType`. If the instance's type corresponds to the `serviceType`, the function returns the current instance; otherwise, it returns `null`, signifying that the service type is not supported by this implementation or the requested service type does not match the instance. Here is a concise breakdown of the conditional logic:

```csharp
public object? GetService(Type serviceType, object? serviceKey = null) =>
    serviceType.IsInstanceOfType(this) ? this : null;
```

This functional query pattern is typically integrated into frameworks to assist in service location or dependency injection scenarios, facilitating runtime determination of available services and modularization of code bases. Interaction with the `Type` class suggests dependencies on reflection mechanisms, important in dynamically typed modules where type conformity must be evaluated at runtime. The absence of iterations or complex branching suggests the method is streamlined for performance under simple type checks.

## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.MixedContentMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` is an asynchronous part of a mock chat client designed to simulate streaming responses in a test environment. It is defined to return a series of `ChatResponseUpdate` objects using `IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>`. Each `ChatResponseUpdate` object contains a collection of content and a role, specified by `Contents` and `Role`, respectively. The contents include `TextContent`, `UriContent`, and `UsageContent`, illustrating the variety of content types that might be managed in real application scenarios.

Upon invocation, the function initiates with `await Task.Delay(1, cancellationToken);`, which obliges the function to handle potential cancellation swiftly with the provided `CancellationToken`. It then sequentially uses the `yield return` mechanism to broadcast several distinct `ChatResponseUpdate` messages. The messages display mixed content such as text for conversational parts, a URI as an image example, and usage statistics that summarize token usage, encapsulated by `UsageContent`. This setup models realistic incremental response behavior in a chat service, catering to automated testing. Dependencies include `ChatMessage`, `ChatOptions`, `TextContent`, `UriContent`, `UsageDetails`, and `ChatRole`, essential elements that populate the chat responses.
````

## Content
````
The class `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient` is an internal sealed implementation designed as a mock of the `IChatClient` interface. The purpose of this class is to facilitate testing scenarios by providing predefined responses for chat interactions, emulating the behavior of an AI chat client in a controlled environment. It supports operations typically expected from a chat client, such as processing chat messages and generating responses, while maintaining simplicity and predictability for unit tests.

Key components within the class include several methods: `GetResponseAsync`, `GetStreamingResponseAsync`, `GetService`, and `Dispose`. The constructor of the class, `SimpleMockChatClient.SimpleMockChatClient`, initializes the object with a predefined response text, allowing it to customize responses for testing without altering the class code. The `GetResponseAsync` method processes input messages to calculate a simulated token usage and returns a `ChatResponse` object constructed with preset metadata and content. The method uses constants and a simple formula to determine the number of "tokens," encapsulated in a `Task`.

In contrast, the `GetStreamingResponseAsync` method mimics streaming responses by yielding individual words from the `_responseText` field one at a time, reflecting tokenized output behavior. It leverages the `async IAsyncEnumerable` to deliver each `ChatResponseUpdate` in sequence, simulating a real-time response stream while incorporating minimal artificial delays and handling cancellation tokens.

The `GetService` method implements a basic service retrieval pattern, using runtime type checking to return the instance itself if it matches the requested service type, thus facilitating dependency injection or service locator scenarios in tests. Meanwhile, the `Dispose` method, while public, serves as a placeholder for disposal operations, adhering to the programming pattern for resource management although it currently performs no actions.

Overall, `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient` is structured to simulate the basic functionality of a chat client, interacting with anticipated input and output patterns expected in unit tests. The class is isolated, without dependencies on external systems or libraries, ensuring it is lightweight and purely focused on testing within the controlled context of the Microsoft AI hosting environment.

# Summary of `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
- Id: `REwDfjbDH4OW9c6WuNQTK/qWySQCWO6MyzMDULFIHXY=`
- Kind: `Symbol`
- Symbol: `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
- SymbolType: `Function`
- Path: `c:\src\alliscode-agent-framework\dotnet\tests\microsoft.agents.ai.hosting.openai.unittests\testhelpers.cs`
## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetResponseAsync` is designed to simulate generating a chat response in a mock environment, primarily for testing purposes. It accepts a collection of chat messages and an optional `ChatOptions` parameter, as well as a `CancellationToken`. These messages are processed to compute a mock message count used to simulate the context size by establishing the number of tokens. The function constructs a predefined `ChatResponse` object, which includes a single `ChatMessage` having the role `ChatRole.Assistant` and preset text stored in `this._responseText`. The `ChatResponse` object captures metadata such as `ModelId`, set to "test-model", and `FinishReason`, set to `ChatFinishReason.Stop`. Additionally, token usage details are calculated based on the number of input messages, with coefficients (10 + number of messages * 5, 5, and 15 + number of messages * 5) that simulate token counts for input, output, and total respectively. This pre-defined response is encapsulated in a `Task` and returned using `Task.FromResult`. The function suggests that it is within a testing environment and does not interact with external systems or libraries for its primary operations.

The function `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetService` is designed to retrieve a service instance from a given type, potentially specified by a service key. This function receives two parameters: `Type serviceType` and an optional `object? serviceKey`. It checks if the `serviceType` parameter is an instance of the current object (`this`). If the object itself is compatible with or equivalently represents the requested service type, the function returns the object itself; otherwise, it returns `null`. The functionality relies on the `Type.IsInstanceOfType` method, which performs runtime type checking to ensure compatibility between `serviceType` and the current instance, such as when implementing dependency injection or service locator patterns.

The purpose of the function is to serve as a simplistic service retrieval mechanism, possibly in unit test scenarios where mock objects are used to simulate real components. This approach allows the function to verify the compatibility of a service type dynamically and potentially facilitate testing operations within test helper contexts, without the need for complex service registration mechanisms. Dependencies inferred from its naming suggest integration with components within the `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests` namespace, assisting in the validation or testing of agent-based or AI-related hosting functionalities, where such mock clients can be used to emulate responses and interactions for unit tests.

# Summary of `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
- Id: `tn80AjHtbnEPmmbK94WIAePDlz3yGC0DTPIEKVPVUyQ=`
- Kind: `Symbol`
- Symbol: `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
- SymbolType: `Function`
- Path: `c:\src\alliscode-agent-framework\dotnet\tests\microsoft.agents.ai.hosting.openai.unittests\testhelpers.cs`
## Symbols
- `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync`
## Content
````
The `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync` function is designed to simulate the behavior of streaming chat responses as an asynchronous enumerable. Its purpose is to process a collection of `ChatMessage` objects, potentially augmented with `ChatOptions`, and employ a simulated stream of text elements derived from a predefined response text, `_responseText`. The function is defined as `async IAsyncEnumerable<ChatResponseUpdate>`, allowing it to yield instances of `ChatResponseUpdate` to the caller asynchronously.

The method begins by simulating minimal processing time using `Task.Delay(1, cancellationToken)`, where `cancellationToken` supports the operation's potential cancellation. The `messages` collection's count is determined to simulate context size, influencing the token usage metrics of the response. Textual streaming is simulated by splitting `_responseText` into individual words and iteratively yielding each as a distinct `ChatResponseUpdate`. For each word, a `ChatResponseUpdate` object is created with the content being a `TextContent` object and a `Role` of `ChatRole.Assistant`. On the last word, additional usage statistics are appended in the form of `UsageContent`, which includes the token counts derived from a simple formula where input tokens depend on the number of input messages. This method executes within a loop, using `yield return` to provide each `ChatResponseUpdate` in sequence, effectively streaming the response word by word. This simulation helps mimic real-world token usage in natural language processing systems.

The constructor `Microsoft.Agents.AI.Hosting.OpenAI.UnitTests.TestHelpers.SimpleMockChatClient.SimpleMockChatClient` is designed to initialize instances of the `SimpleMockChatClient` class, which is presumably a utility for generating mock responses in testing scenarios. It accepts a single parameter, `responseText`, which defaults to the string "Test response" if no argument is provided. This constructor assigns the `responseText` parameter to a private field `_responseText`, internalizing the input for future use within the class. The constructor does not contain any conditional logic, loops, or external dependencies; it solely serves the purpose of setting up the initial state of the `SimpleMockChatClient` instance by storing the provided or default response text. By allowing customization through the `responseText` parameter, this constructor facilitates flexibility in testing scenarios, enabling varied responses without modifying the core class logic. Here is the constructor's core initialization logic:
```csharp
public SimpleMockChatClient(string responseText = "Test response")
{
    this._responseText = responseText;
}
```
